-matter of the volume is uncommonly wide-ranging and the studies collected here inquire into many important issues of Plutarchean scholarship: the conditions under which Plutarch's writings were separated into two distinct corpora, his methods of work and the various authorial techniques employed, the interplay between Lives and Moralia, Plutarch and politics, Plutarch and philosophy, literary aspects of Plutarch's œuvre, Plutarch on women, Plutarch in his epistemological and socio-historical context. In sum, this book brings Plutarchean scholarship to date by revisiting and discussing older and recent problematization concerning Plutarch, in an attempt to further illuminate his personality and work.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aGreek literaturexCriticism and interpretationvCongresses. 4aPlutarch. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aPlutarch.1 aAguilar, Rosa Ma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexiou, Evangelos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsh, Rhiannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeneker, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillault, Alain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlois, Lukas de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulet, Bernard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulogne, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowie, Ewen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re